FINGER LAKES REGION, NEW YORK STATE

Leif Ericson landed in the East, and he called this continent

“Vinland.” Right he was, for more grape varieties flourish on this side of the Rockies than in any other equal area of the world. Unlike California wines, which are made from

vines of European origin, Eastern wines are produced from

native American species and their hybrids. he very names

of the grapes, Catawba, Delaware, Elvira, Iona, sound as

American as a poem by Walt Whitman. Judged purely by

wine standards, the most important of the Finger Lakes are

Lake Keuka and Lake Canandaigua. From the shores of

Lake Canandaigua come some of the country’s finest white,

dry table wines. ‘Those produced at the impressive old winery

operated by the Widmer Brothers are particularly outstand-

2 Hillside Rhine, Widmer Bros. A skillful blend of Eastern grape varieties with the Delawares, Elviras and Catawbas predominating. A satisfactory everyday table wine.

Lake Elvira 1939, Widmer Bros.

Pale straw in color. Elvira has a delightful fragrance reminiscent of a young Moselle. Our favorite among Eastern wines.

: aoe 2 re SD. Lake Delaware 1939, Widmer Bros. We thought this young thoroughbred sprightly and fresh when first we tasted it at William Widmer’s Lake Canandaigua home. Repeated tasting has con firmed our original fondness.

Lake Diana 1939, Widmer Bros.

An offspring of the Catawba, this grape was named in 1834 after the originator, Mrs. Diana Crehore of Milton, Massachusetts. Possesses the characteristic freshness and flowery bouquet of the native white wine grape.
